WRITING.TITLE: Graduated college yesterday, went hunting before hand and got my first ever bird on the next to last day of the season!

WRITING.TEXT: no haha, I had a 2pm ceremony. had perfect timing to hunt, check it in, drive home, clean it, shower, dress up and got their right on time.

Story: Went hunting in Robertson county, TN on my roommates families property, usually he goes with me but he was out of town on family vacation. I got into the woods around 430, set up and after about 15 mins I heard some gobbles off to my left at the base of the bluff, decided that they were too far to probably call in. After a few more minutes I heard one on the other side of the gully that I was facing, so I decided to try to work this bird in. After a while with very light calling, the bird had wondered off else where. Around 6:20am, I noticed that it had been very quiet for a while and knew I needed to try something different. There had been some very light rain, and I'd always heard that rain pushes turkeys to the field earlier. So I snuck back up through the woods/hill. As soon as I looked out I saw a Flock(I'm guessing thats what you call a group of turkeys? Please correct me if I'm wrong) about 200-250yards away, so I decided to sneak through the woods to the corner closest that I could that we've seen them enter and exit from. After walking that way some I heard a gobble off in the distance, I had to choose whether or not to try to work that bird in or keep going to the ones I'd seen. I choose to move towards the birds I'd seen. When I finally got to the corner, I glanced out carefully and saw a Jake about 45 yards away, It was walking towards me on its own. The jake was clucking and purring alot too, I heard a gobble off to the left in response to it, so I wanted to wait to see if a bigger bird would come in. After a while and no other bird showing up, the Jake turned around and started walking off. Right before it was out of range I pulled out the box call and clucked twice at him, he turned around and walked right back to me. I took the shot at around 20-25 yards. Had it not been the next to last day of the season, my last chance to hunt, and the first time we had a bird in range, I would have let him go. But it did add to an already memorable day. Bird was taken with a Stoeger STF2000 12 gauge. TL;DR went hunting graduation morning, after a while of no luck, spotted turkeys in the field, moved through woods, got in range of a Jake, took the shot at around 20-25yards. Taken on Stoeger STF2000 12 gauge.
